        <section class="max" id="properties">
            <h3 class="text-5xl font-nunito py-5 text-primary">Properties Information</h3>

            <div class="info">
                <h4>Float</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The float CSS property places an element on the left or right side of its container, allowing
                    text and
                    inline elements to wrap around it.</p>
                <h4>Display</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The display CSS property sets whether an element is treated as a block or inline element and
                    the layout
                    used for its children, such as flow layout, grid or flex.</p>
                <h4>Position</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The position CSS property sets how an element is positioned in a document. The top, right,
                    bottom, and
                    left properties determine the final location of positioned elements.</p>
                <h4>Left, Right, Top, Bottom</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The left, right, top, and bottom properties are used to position elements in a container. They
                    specify
                    the distance of the element from the respective side of the container.</p>
                <h4>Width and Height</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The width and height CSS properties set the width and height of an element's content box.</p>
                <h4>Max-width and Min-width</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The max-width and min-width CSS properties set the maximum and minimum width of an element's
                    content box.
                </p>
                <h4>Max-height and Min-height</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The max-height and min-height CSS properties set the maximum and minimum height of an
                    element's content
                    box.</p>
                <h4>Margin</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The margin CSS property sets the margin area on all four sides of an element. It is a
                    shorthand for
                    setting margin-top, margin-right, margin-bottom, and margin-left.</p>
                <h4>Padding</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The padding CSS property sets the padding area on all four sides of an element. It is a
                    shorthand for
                    setting padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, and padding-left.</p>
                <h4>Font-family</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The font-family CSS property specifies a prioritized list of one or more font family names
                    and/or generic
                    family names for an element.</p>
                <h4>Font-size</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The font-size CSS property sets the size of the font.</p>
                <h4>Font-weight</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The font-weight CSS property sets the weight (or boldness) of the font.</p>
                <h4>Letter-spacing</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The letter-spacing CSS property sets the horizontal spacing between letters.</p>
                <h4>Color</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The color CSS property sets the foreground color value of an element's text and text
                    decorations.</p>
                <h4>Line-height</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The line-height CSS property sets the height of a line box.</p>
                <h4>Text-align</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The text-align CSS property sets the horizontal alignment of a block element or table-cell
                    box.</p>
                <h4>Text-decoration</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The text-decoration CSS property sets the appearance of decorative lines on text.</p>
                <h4>Text-shadow</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The text-shadow CSS property adds shadows to text.</p>
                <h4>Opacity</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The opacity CSS property sets the opacity level for an element.</p>
                <h4>Border-radius</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The border-radius CSS property rounds the corners of an element's outer border edge.</p>
                <h4>Box-shadow</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The box-shadow CSS property adds shadow effects around an element's frame.</p>
                <h4>Background</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The background CSS property is a shorthand property that sets all background properties in one
                    declaration.</p>
                <h4>Transition</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The transition CSS property is a shorthand property for setting the four transition properties
                    into a
                    single declaration.</p>
                <h4>Perspective</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The perspective CSS property determines the distance between the z=0 plane and the user in
                    order to give
                    a 3D-positioned element some perspective.</p>
                <h4>Transform</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The transform CSS property lets you rotate, scale, skew, or translate an element.</p>

                <h4>ID</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The id attribute is used to give an element a unique identifier within a document. It is used
                    to target
                    an element with CSS or JavaScript.</p>
                <h4>Title</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The title attribute is used to provide additional information about an element. It is often
                    used to
                    provide tooltips or other supplemental content.</p>
                <h4>HREF</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The href attribute is used in the <a> element to specify the link's destination. It is the
                        most common
                        way to create hyperlinks on the web.</p>
                <h4>Target</h4>
                <p> &emsp;The target attribute is used in the <a> element to specify where to open the linked document.
                        It can have
                        values such as \_self (open in the same frame), \_blank (open in a new tab), and \_parent (open
                        in
                        the parent frame).</p>
            </div>
